%spark2.pyspark
import pandas as pd
import urllib
import glob
import gc

pd.set_option('display.expand_frame_repr', True)
pd.options.display.max_columns = None

# Collect all data to one Pandas Dataframe
list_usage = []
path ='/home/hadoop/TFL_Cycling_Data_raw/usage-stats_example'
allFiles = glob.glob(path + "/*.csv")
for file_ in allFiles:
    df = pd.read_csv(file_,index_col=None, header=0)
    list_usage.append(df)
    gc.collect()

cycleusage_df = pd.concat(list_usage, axis = 0, sort=False, ignore_index = True)
cycleusage_df = cycleusage_df.fillna(value=0)
cycleusage_df.head()
#Causes problem -> out of memory because we don't have around 5 GB storage left anymore.

%md
###File sizing###
Problem: too many files for one dataframe (size bigger then free memory allocation).
Idea: put each single file into a new folder on the HDFS and use Spark for reading file by file.
- Data munging (i.e. remove unused columns for saving memory, get coordinates, merge frames)
- Use read parallelize method of Spark API
- Convert RDD to DF and save it back to HDFS

File sizing

Problem: too many files for one dataframe (size bigger then free memory allocation).
Idea: put each single file into a new folder on the HDFS and use Spark for reading file by file.

  • Data munging (i.e. remove unused columns for saving memory, get coordinates, merge frames)
  • Use read parallelize method of Spark API
  • Convert RDD to DF and save it back to HDFS

%sh

# Remove old dataset if already exists in hadoop /user/hadoop directory
d_name=/user/hadoop/usage-stats/

hdfs dfs -test -d $d_name
    if [ $? != 0 ]
            then
                echo "Move folder to HDFS..."
                hdfs dfs -put /home/hadoop/TFL_Cycling_Data_raw/usage-stats /user/hadoop/usage-stats
                echo "Folder successfully uploaded to HDFS"
                hdfs dfs -ls $d_name
            else
                echo "Directory already present in HDFS"
                echo "Move folder to trash"
                hdfs dfs -rm -r -skipTrash $d_name
                echo "$d_name" "has been deleted"
    fi

%spark2

%spark2.pyspark

rdd_usage = spark.read.csv("/user/hadoop/usage-stats/*.csv", header=True)
#Took 12 seconds to read 38.122.372 lines

rdd_usage.show()

rdd_usage = rdd_usage.na.fill(0)
#sqlContext.clearCache()
#rdd_usage.unpersist()

%spark2.pyspark
from pyspark.sql.functions import *
rdd_usage.createOrReplaceTempView("table_df")
query_latest_rec = """SELECT * FROM table_df ORDER BY 'StartStation Id'LIMIT 25"""
latest_rec = sqlContext.sql(query_latest_rec)
latest_rec.show()

#rdd_usage.select("*").where((rdd_usage["StartStation Id"] == "463") & (rdd_usage["EndStation Id"] == "148")).show()

%spark2.pyspark

#Group by ID count and store it on an aditional column
rdd_usage2 = rdd_usage.groupBy(['StartStation Id']).count().select('*', f.col('count').alias('StartStation Id Used'))
rdd_usage2.show()
##Problem, StartStation ID seems to have also dates
#Therefore let's do at first some preparation steps

%spark2.pyspark
##Dont use toPandas() -> trying to load everything in one Workers Node
#d = rdd_usage.toPandas()
#rdd_usage.select("").show()

#rdd_usage.DataFrame
rdd_usage.dropna(subset=["StartStation Id", "EndStation Id", "Start Date", "End Date"])


#Change column types of ID columns
rdd_usage = rdd_usage.withColumn("EndStation ID", rdd_usage["EndStation ID"].cast("int"))
rdd_usage = rdd_usage.withColumn("StartStation ID", rdd_usage["StartStation ID"].cast("int"))

#Prevent StartStation ID = EndStation ID
rdd_usage = rdd_usage[rdd_usage["StartStation Id"] != rdd_usage["EndStation Id"]]


#Keep only relevant columns
rdd_usage = rdd_usage["Start Date", "StartStation Id", "End Date", "EndStation Id", "Duration"]

rdd_usage.printSchema()

rdd_usage_esc = rdd_usage.groupBy(['EndStation Id']).count().select("EndStation Id", col('count').alias('EndStation Id Used'))

ta = rdd_usage.alias('ta')
tb = rdd_usage_ssc.alias('tb')
tc = rdd_usage_esc.alias('tc')

ta = rdd_usage2.alias('ta')
rdd_usage2 = ta.join(tc, ta["EndStation Id"] == tc["End Id"], "left_outer")

msg.data:
Getting rentalstation coordinates

TfL have a live “cycle hire updates” feed which lists information for each cycle hire station, updated once every minute.
Provides full details of rentail stations name, ID, lat/lon, and capacity.

paragraphs.text:
%spark2.pyspark
import requests
from xml.etree import ElementTree as ET
import pandas as pd

#Getting the coordinates tuples of the rental stations
site = "https://tfl.gov.uk/tfl/syndication/feeds/cycle-hire/livecyclehireupdates.xml"
response = requests.get(site)
root = ET.fromstring(response.content)

#fetch relevant information
id_list = [int(root[i][0].text) for i in range(0, len(root))]
name_list = [root[i][1].text for i in range(0, len(root))]
lat_list = [float(root[i][3].text) for i in range(0, len(root))]
lon_list = [float(root[i][4].text) for i in range(0, len(root))]
capacity_list = [int(root[i][12].text) for i in range(0, len(root))]

#zip tuples
all_locs = pd.DataFrame(list(zip(name_list, id_list, lat_list, 
                                 lon_list, capacity_list)), columns = ["name","id","lat","lon","capacity"])

#zip
all_locs.to_csv('/home/hadoop/TFL_Cycling_Data_raw/rental_stations_saved.csv', header=True, index=None)
print(all_locs.shape)

#786 unique rental stations
all_locs.head()

%spark2.pyspark
from pyspark.sql.functions import *

#Load saved rental stations location
rdd_rental_locs = spark.read.csv("/user/hadoop/rental_stations_saved.csv", header=True)
rdd_rental_locs.printSchema()
rdd_rental_locs.show()
rdd_rental_locs.count()

#Drop duplicated Station IDs
unq_rentals = rdd_usage["StartStation Id", "EndStation Id", "Duration", "StartStation Id Used", "EndStation Id Used"]
print("With duplicates: ", unq_rentals.count())
unq_rentals = unq_rentals.dropDuplicates()
print("Without duplicates: ", unq_rentals.count())

##Merging
#Merge cycle_usage RDD with RDD from livecyclehireupdates for StartStations
ta = unq_rentals.alias('ta')
tb = rdd_rental_locs.alias('tb')
unq_rentals = ta.join(tb, ta["StartStation Id"] == tb.id)
#Drop unncessary id column and rename name to StartStation Address
#Dropping column requires to reorganize the RDD
unq_rentals = unq_rentals.drop('id')
unq_rentals = unq_rentals.withColumnRenamed("name", "StartStation Address").withColumnRenamed("lat", "StartStation  latitude").withColumnRenamed("lon", "StartStation longitude").withColumnRenamed("capacity", "StartStation capacity")
unq_rentals.show()

#for EndStations
ta = unq_rentals.alias('ta')
unq_rentals = ta.join(tb, ta["EndStation Id"] == tb.id)
unq_rentals = unq_rentals.drop("id")
unq_rentals = unq_rentals.withColumnRenamed("name", "EndStation Address").withColumnRenamed("lat", "EndStation  latitude").withColumnRenamed("lon", "EndStation longitude").withColumnRenamed("capacity", "EndStation capacity")
unq_rentals.show()

%spark2.pyspark

#Write back on HDFS in one single csv file
unq_rentals.coalesce(1).write.csv("/user/hadoop/usage_stats_prepared", header=True)

#### Summary ####
1. The sizing problem can be well handled by Spark

3. For plotting tasks packages like folium or seaborn can not be used with Spark DataFrame
    * Converting back to Pandas DF might exceed RAM cache (swap)
    * Using Jupyter notebook on local computer for plotting maps (e.g. folium)
